Locally known as the "cemetery in the backyard," once laid the remains of what was actually named the Centerville Cemetery. Dating back nearly 175 years, this old boneyard was one of many small Jewish cemeteries scattered around the New Jersey and New York area. The stones were scribed in Hebrew, nearly indistinguishable. Mount Nebo, a more modern and upkept cemetery was later opened in Totowa, therefore this one was no longer useful. As many of these old graveyards, it fell into severe disrepair and one day the stones were removed: presumably along with the bodies of the deceased? (Information provided by Kathy Grimshaw-Haven; Head of History and Reference at the Clifton Public Library).
